{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540042"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:50:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:50:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16732"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16732"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.47,0.13,0.21,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9423"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66645"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9423"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16732"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52098"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11109"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43650"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66645"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for advice about contraception. She has a history of latex allergy causing contact urticaria. She does not want hormonal contraception. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She works as a nurse and is in a monogamous relationship. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about non-latex condoms for this patient is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["They are more likely to break during intercourse","They have similar pregnancy rates to latex condoms","They are effective against all sexually transmitted infections","They cannot be used with oil-based lubricants","They are only available on prescription"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFor patients with latex allergy who desire non-hormonal contraception, non-latex condoms are an appropriate option. The two main types are polyurethane and synthetic polyisoprene condoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimilar pregnancy rates to latex condoms\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. Clinical studies have shown that non-latex condoms have comparable effectiveness to latex condoms when used correctly and consistently, with typical-use pregnancy rates of around 13% per year for both types.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMore likely to break during intercourse\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While early polyurethane condoms had slightly higher breakage rates, modern non-latex condoms have similar breakage rates to latex condoms when used correctly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEffective against all sexually transmitted infections\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While non-latex condoms provide good protection against most sexually transmitted infections, their effectiveness is similar to latex condoms and neither type provides complete protection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOnly available on prescription\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Non-latex condoms are readily available over the counter at pharmacies and other retailers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECannot be used with oil-based lubricants\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Unlike latex condoms which degrade with oil-based lubricants, polyurethane condoms can be used with all types of lubricants. However, water-based lubricants are still recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELatex allergy affects approximately 1% of the general population and up to 10% of healthcare workers. Symptoms can range from mild contact dermatitis to severe anaphylaxis. For these patients, non-latex condoms provide a safe and effective contraceptive option.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Non-latex condoms are an effective alternative for patients with latex allergy, with similar pregnancy rates to latex condoms.","Polyurethane and polyisoprene condoms are the main alternatives to latex condoms.","Latex allergy affects approximately 1% of the general population and 10% of healthcare workers."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Contraception: Clinical Guideline [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Dec 1]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Contraception-Clinical-Guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52098"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16732"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52098"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T17:49:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T17:51:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9423"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66645"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"